Linux Command Cheat Sheet

Basic Commands

cd: Change directory.

touch: Create a file or modify its timestamp.

file: Identify the type of a file.

echo: Print text to the terminal.

cat: View the full contents of a file.

cp: Copy files from one directory to another.

mv: Move or rename files.

ls: List files and directories in the current directory.

pwd: Show the present working directory.

ls -la: List files in long format with detailed information.

less: View large files page by page (allows scrolling up and down).

more: View large files page by page (cannot scroll up).

tail: View the last lines of a file.

head: View the first n lines of a file.

man: View the manual pages for a command.

help: Show help for a command (similar to man).

Redirection

>: Redirect standard output to a file (overwrite).

>>: Redirect standard output to a file (append).

<: Redirect input from a file.

2>: Redirect error messages to a file.

2>&1 or &>: Redirect both standard output and error to a file.

Background Processes

nohup: Run a command immune to hangups, with output to a file.

disown: Remove jobs from the shell's job table (used with background jobs).

Append & to run a command in the background.

Pipes and Filters

|: Pipe output of one command as input to another.

grep: Search for patterns in files.

sed: Stream editor for searching, deleting, inserting, and replacing text.

Use with caution: sed -i modifies files in place.

Use sed -n to print specific patterns.

cut: Extract sections from each line of input.

tr: Translate or delete characters.

tee: Redirect output to multiple destinations.

System Monitoring

top: View live processes and resource usage.

htop: Interactive process viewer (alternative to top).

df: Show disk space usage.

find: Locate files (e.g., find / -name "filename").

lsblk: List block devices.

free: Show memory usage.

vmstat: Report system performance.

File Permissions

chmod: Change file permissions.

chown: Change file owner.

chgrp: Change file group.

Permission Values

Read = 4

Write = 2

Execute = 1

Example: 777 means full read, write, execute for user, group, and others.

Special Permissions

Setuid (set user ID): Execute file with owner's privileges (chmod u+s filename).

Setgid (set group ID): Execute file with group's privileges.

Sticky bit: Only file owner can delete/modify files in a directory with 777 permissions.

User Management

adduser / useradd: Add a new user.

usermod: Modify an existing user.

userdel: Delete a user.

addgroup: Add a new group.

passwd: Change user password.

sudo: Execute commands as superuser.

su -s user: Switch user.

Process Management

nohup: Run process in background ignoring hangup signals.

jobs: List current shell jobs (running, stopped).

ps aux: Snapshot of running processes with CPU, memory, PID.

kill: Terminate a process by PID.

kill -9: Forcefully terminate a process.

nice: Start a process with a given priority.

renice: Change priority of existing processes (-20 highest, 19 lowest).

Signals

SIGKILL: Force kill.

SIGTERM: Graceful shutdown.

SIGINT: Interrupt (Ctrl + C).

SIGSTOP: Pause process.

SIGCONT: Resume paused process.

Scheduling Tasks

cron jobs: Schedule tasks to run at specific times.

crontab -e: Edit cron jobs.

Cron Format

* * * * * /full/path/to/script_or_command

Other Useful Commands

timedatectl: View and manage system time settings.

lsof: List open files by processes.


Filesystem Check

fsck /dev/sdX: Check and repair filesystem consistency on the specified device.

Swap Management

Swap acts like RAM on disk; when RAM is full, swap space is used to keep applications running smoothly and avoid system crashes.

mkswap: Initialize swap space.

swapon /dev/sdX: Enable swap on the specified device.

swapoff /dev/sdX: Disable swap on the specified device.
Networking

ss - Display socket statistics (ports, connections)

traceroute - Trace packet route

ping - Send echo requests to test connectivity (e.g., ping -c 3 google.com)

ifconfig - Display network interfaces and IP addresses

arp - Show IP to MAC address mappings

route -n - Show routing table

tcpdump -i interface - Capture network packets

Debugging

strace - Trace system calls from user to kernel mode

